<section xml:id="sec_fourth-examplesA" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Examples A</title>
  
<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the tension in each of the strings of the system shown here:
     </p>
     <image source="steq1.png" width="30%"> </image> 
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <term>Step 1.</term> List the given quantities and label the diagram:
      </p>
      <image source="steq1a.png" width="35%"> </image>  
    <p>
      <term>Step 2.</term> Isolate each object and draw the force diagrams:
      <sidebyside widths="30% 10% 10%">
        <image source="steq1b.png" width="30%"> </image>  
        <image source="steq1bb.png" width="10%"> </image>  
        <image source="steq1bc.png" width="10%"> </image> 
      </sidebyside>
        </p>
        <p>
      <term>Step 3.</term> Resolve forces into components as shown in figure:
       </p>
       <image source="steq1c.png" width="40%"> </image> 
    <p>
     <term> Step 4.</term> Write equations using the figure 
    </p>
     <image source="steq1c.png" width="40%"> </image> 
     <p>
      <me>
      \sum{F_{x}} =  T_{2}\cos\theta - T_{1}\sin\theta   =  0
     </me>
     <me>
      \sum{F_{y}} = T_{2}\sin\theta - T_{1}\cos\theta -T_{3}=  0
     </me>
    from figure  <image source="steq1bb.png" width="10%"> </image>  
    <me>
      \sum{F_{y}} = T_{3}-w_{1}-T_{4}=  0
    </me>
    from figure <image source="steq1bc.png" width="10%"> </image>  
    <me>
      \sum{F_{y}} = T_{4}-w_{2} = 0
    </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      <term>Step 5.</term> Solve equations simultaneously for unknowns:
      <me>
        T_{4}  =  w_{2} =  10 N 
      </me>
      <me>
        T_{3}  =  T_{4} + w_{1} = 30 N
      </me>
      <me>
        Now,\quad T_{2} = \frac{T_{1}\sin\theta}{\cos\theta}= T_{1}\tan\theta
      </me>
      <me>
        also,\quad T_{1} = \frac{T_{3}}{\tan\theta\sin\theta-\cos\theta} = 30N; 
      </me>
      <me>
        \therefore T_{2} =52 N
      </me>
      </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the tension in each of the strings of the system below if the weight <m>w=80N</m> 
      and the angle <m>\theta=30^{o}</m>.   
    </p>
    <image source="fe1a.png" width="35%"> </image>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
     From figure <image source="fe1b.png" width="60%"> </image> 
     <me>
      \sum F_{x} =T_{2}\sin\theta-T_{1}\cos\theta =0 
    </me>
     <men xml:id="eqn-fe1a">
      \text{or,}\quad T_{1}=T_{2}\tan\theta =T_{2}\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} 
    </men>
    <me>
      \sum F_{y} =T_{2}\cos\theta+T_{1}\sin\theta-T_{3} =0 
    </me>
    <me>
      \text{or,}\quad T_{2}\cos 30^{o}+T_{1}\sin 30^{o} =80 
    </me>
    <men xml:id="eqn-fe1b">
      \text{or,}\quad T_{2}\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}+T_{1}\frac{1}{2} =T_{3} 
    </men>
      <me>
        \sum F_{y}=T_{3}-w=0
      </me>
      <men xml:id="eqn-fe1c">
        T_{3}=w=80N 
      </men>
      from eqns. <xref ref="eqn-fe1a"/>, <xref ref="eqn-fe1b"/>, and <xref ref="eqn-fe1c"/>, we have
      <me>
        T_{2}=70N  \quad \text{and} \quad T_{1}=40N 
      </me>
      </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A 5 kg block is held at rest against a vertical wall by a horizontal force of 100N. 
      <ol marker="a.">
        <li>
          What is the frictional force exerted by the wall on the block? 
        </li>
        <li>
          What is the minimum horizontal force needed to prevent the block from sliding 
          down the wall if the coefficient of static friction between the wall and the block is <m>0.4</m>?
        </li>
      </ol>
       </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <image source="steq2ab.png" width="20%"> </image> 
    <p>
      Given: <m>m= 5kg, \quad w= mg = 5kg\cdot9.8 m/s^{2} =49N,\quad F=100 N.</m>
       <ol marker="a.">
        <li>
          <me>
            \sum F_{x}=F-N=0 \quad\Rightarrow\quad F=N=100N
          </me>
          <me>
            \sum F_{y}=f-w=0\quad\Rightarrow\quad f=w=49N
          </me>
          </li>
        <li>
          <me>
            f=\mu_{s}N \qquad\Rightarrow\quad N=\frac{f}{\mu_{s}}=\frac{49N}{0.4}=122N
          </me>
          </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

